<Base title="How It Works" active="how-it-works">
  <div class="container">

    <section class="page-header">
      <h3>The Full Walkthrough</h3>
      <h1>How It Works</h1>
      <p>From microphone to finished mix &mdash; a complete guide to every piece of gear, every creative decision, and every step of the process. No jargon, no prerequisites, just the full story of how sound becomes a record.</p>
    </section>

    <div class="vu-bar"></div>

    <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════
         INTRODUCTION
         ════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <article class="hiw">

      <section class="hiw__section" id="intro">
        <div class="prose">
          <h3>A Studio That Works Like a Record</h3>
          <p>
            This is a home studio that works like a professional one. Not a laptop with a USB microphone and some software &mdash; a room with a rack of analog hardware, a digital mixing console, a physical fader board, and an AI assistant that controls it all. We record vocals and guitar through real electronic circuits that add warmth, weight, and polish to the sound before it ever hits the recorder. We build songs one layer at a time. And when every layer is down, we mix them on a physical console with real faders, capturing the mix as a live performance.
          </p>
          <h3>Three Promises</h3>
          <p>
            We make three promises. The first is zero latency &mdash; a term that means no delay between what you play and what you hear. When you sing into the microphone, you hear your voice in the headphones at the exact same instant, processed through the full chain of analog gear. There is no perceptible gap, no echo of yourself arriving a fraction of a second late. This matters more than most people realize: even a tiny delay between your voice leaving your mouth and arriving in your ears throws off your pitch, your timing, your confidence. We eliminate that entirely by processing everything in hardware, not software.
          </p>
          <p>
            The second promise is that every take sounds like a finished record before we even start mixing. The analog gear &mdash; the preamp that adds body, the compressors that control dynamics, the de-esser that tames harshness &mdash; all of that processing is committed to the recording permanently. This is not a rough scratch track that we will "fix in the mix." It is the sound. When you listen back to a take, you are hearing what the audience will hear. That kind of immediacy changes how you perform, because you trust the sound coming back to you.
          </p>
          <p>
            The third promise is the most unusual: an AI assistant runs the mixing board. Not generating music, not making creative decisions, but handling the engineering. Every parameter on the digital mixer &mdash; hundreds of faders, mutes, routing assignments, effect settings &mdash; can be read and changed through plain-language commands. "Set up for lead guitar." "Add reverb to the vocal." "Something sounds wrong with the drums." The AI finds the right channels, checks the current state, makes the changes, and confirms. The musician never needs to touch the console or learn its interface.
          </p>
          <h3>The Journey Ahead</h3>
          <p>
            What follows is the full journey, from the moment you plug in an instrument to the moment a finished mix rolls off the console. We will walk through every piece of gear, explain what it does and why it matters, describe the recording process layer by layer, explain how mixing works on a physical board, and show you what it looks like when an AI runs the engineering side of a recording session. This is the definitive guide to how this studio works.
          </p>
        </div>

