      <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════
           PART 4: RECORDING
           ════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <section class="hiw__section" id="recording">
        <span class="hiw__part-label">Part 4</span>
        <h2>Recording &mdash; Building a Song Layer by Layer <a href="#recording" class="hiw__anchor"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path d="M10 13a5 5 0 0 0 7.54.54l3-3a5 5 0 0 0-7.07-7.07l-1.72 1.71"/><path d="M14 11a5 5 0 0 0-7.54-.54l-3 3a5 5 0 0 0 7.07 7.07l1.71-1.71"/></svg></a></h2>
        <div class="prose">
          <h3>The First Take</h3>
          <p>
            Logic Pro is our tape machine. For anyone unfamiliar, Logic Pro is Apple's professional music production software, and in our studio it serves the same role that a reel-to-reel tape recorder served in studios of the 1960s and 70s: it captures the audio. But where a tape machine gives you a fixed number of tracks on a fixed length of tape, Logic gives us unlimited tracks, unlimited length, full undo, and non-destructive editing. We can record a hundred takes of the same vocal line and compare them all. We can cut a verse from take three and paste it next to a chorus from take seven. The flexibility is extraordinary, but the important thing is what we record onto those tracks: the fully processed signal from the outboard chain, with all the preamp warmth and compression already baked in.
          </p>
          <h3>Unlimited Tape</h3>
          <p>
            The audio travels from the mixer to the computer over USB &mdash; a single cable carrying dozens of independent audio channels simultaneously, each one a separate stream of digital audio. Think of it like a multi-lane highway: the vocal recording rides in one lane, the guitar recording in another, and they never merge or interfere. On the computer side, Logic receives each channel on its own track, ready to record. The signal that arrives has already been through the full outboard chain &mdash; preamp, compressors, de-esser &mdash; so what Logic captures is the finished sound, not a raw scratch track waiting to be processed later.
          </p>
          <h3>Layering</h3>
          <p>
            Songs are built one layer at a time. Record the vocal. Listen back and record guitar on top. Listen to both and add a harmony. Each new layer plays in your headphones while you perform the next one.
          </p>
          <p>
            A typical session goes like this: you sing the melody first. That take gets captured in Logic. Then you switch to guitar. Now you hear your recorded vocal in the headphones while you play along with it &mdash; both at the same time. The guitar goes onto its own track. Next, maybe a harmony vocal. You hear the original vocal and the guitar while you sing the harmony. Each layer stacks on top of the last.
          </p>
          <p>
            This is called overdubbing. The key is that playback and recording never interfere &mdash; they use completely separate signal paths. What is playing back from Logic comes in on one set of channels. What is being recorded goes out on a different set. They only meet in the headphones. So you can record and listen back at the same time, with no bleed between them.
          </p>
          <h3>The AI Band</h3>
          <p>
            Logic also has a feature called session players &mdash; AI-generated instruments that can provide bass, drums, keyboards, and synthesizer parts in any style and tempo. These are not pre-recorded loops; they are dynamically generated performances that follow the chord progression and feel of the song. During tracking, the session players play back through the mixer alongside the recorded takes, giving the musician a full backing band in the headphones. The bass locks to the root notes, the drums provide the groove, and the keys fill out the harmony. It is like having a rehearsal band that never gets tired and always knows the changes.
          </p>
          <p>
            The result of all this layering is a Logic project with multiple tracks, each one a fully processed recording of a single performance, all perfectly synchronized. The vocal was recorded through the outboard chain. The guitar was recorded through the outboard chain with a different compressor. The harmony was recorded through the vocal chain again. The session players were generated by the software. All of these layers now exist as independent tracks, ready for the mixing stage.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="hiw__svg-wrap">
          <svg viewBox="0 0 700 340" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" role="img" aria-label="Seven tracks stacking up in Logic Pro — recorded performances and AI session players">
