      <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════
           PART 6: MIXING
           ════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <section class="hiw__section" id="mixing">
        <span class="hiw__part-label">Part 6</span>
        <h2>Mixing &mdash; Playing the Console <a href="#mixing" class="hiw__anchor"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path d="M10 13a5 5 0 0 0 7.54.54l3-3a5 5 0 0 0-7.07-7.07l-1.72 1.71"/><path d="M14 11a5 5 0 0 0-7.54-.54l-3 3a5 5 0 0 0 7.07 7.07l1.71-1.71"/></svg></a></h2>
        <div class="prose">
          <h3>What Mixing Actually Is</h3>
          <p>
            Mixing is the art of taking all the individual tracks we have recorded &mdash; the vocal, the rhythm guitar, the lead guitar, the harmonies, the bass, the drums, the keyboards &mdash; and balancing them so they sound like one cohesive piece of music rather than seven things happening at the same time. It is about volume relationships (the vocal needs to be louder than the guitar during the verse but maybe not during the solo), frequency balance (the bass and the kick drum should not fight each other for space in the low end), and spatial placement (some instruments should feel close, others distant, some centered, others wide). Mixing is where a collection of good recordings becomes a song.
          </p>
          <h3>Effects and Stems</h3>
          <p>
            When all the layers are recorded, the song moves to the mixing stage. All tracks play back from Logic through the Wing, which is where the first round of processing happens. The Wing adds effects that shape the character of each element: plate reverb on the vocal to give it a sense of space, a vocal doubler that thickens the voice with a subtle chorus effect, a sub-octave generator that adds weight and presence to the bass line, and amp simulations on the guitar playback tracks to give them their final tone. The Wing also applies high-pass and low-pass filters across all the mix buses &mdash; rolling off the very lowest rumble below 60 Hz (frequencies you feel more than hear, and which waste headroom) and taming the extreme high frequencies above 14 kHz (which can sound shrill on small speakers).
          </p>
          <p>
            After the Wing applies its processing, it splits the audio into seven stems &mdash; groups of related tracks bundled together. Vocals on one stem, rhythm guitar on another, lead guitar on a third, overdubs (harmonies and additional parts) on a fourth, bass on a fifth, drums on a sixth, and piano or synth on a seventh. These seven stems travel from the Wing to the Tascam Model 12.
          </p>
          <h3>Physical Faders</h3>
          <p>
            The Model 12 is a physical mixing console &mdash; a real piece of hardware with real faders (sliding volume controls), real knobs for EQ (tone shaping), and real analog signal paths. Each of the seven stems lands on its own fader, and this is where mixing becomes a physical, tactile experience. Why use a physical console when the Wing could balance everything digitally? Because there is something irreplaceable about having your hands on the controls. Moving a fader with your fingers is faster and more intuitive than clicking and dragging on a screen. You can grab two faders at once &mdash; pushing the vocal up while pulling the guitar down &mdash; in a way that requires two mouse clicks in software. Muscle memory develops: you learn where the vocal fader lives in the verse, in the chorus, in the bridge. The physical console turns mixing from a cerebral, screen-based activity into a performance.
          </p>
          <h3>Every Pass Is a Take</h3>
          <p>
            And we mean that literally. The Model 12 is always recording its stereo output on tracks 11 and 12 &mdash; a continuous two-track capture of whatever the faders produce. Every mix pass is a live performance, captured in real time. We play the song from the top, ride the faders through the arrangement, make real-time decisions about balance and dynamics, and the result is a stereo mix. Then we do it again. And maybe again. Each pass is a different take on the same song, and the best mix wins. This is how records were mixed before computers: the engineer performed the mix, committed to it, and moved on. There is no undo, no "let me try that chorus again." The constraint forces decisiveness, and decisiveness produces mixes with energy and intention.
          </p>
          <p>
            The contrast with modern software mixing is stark. In a DAW (digital audio workstation), mixing is infinite. You can undo any change, automate every fader move to a precise timeline, A/B between forty different reverb settings. Great mixes happen in DAWs every day &mdash; the tool does not determine the outcome. But for us, the physical console changes how we listen. The constraint of a live pass keeps us moving forward instead of second-guessing. Our approach does not reject technology (the Wing is a sophisticated digital processor), but it embraces the idea that the final step &mdash; the moment where balance becomes art &mdash; feels best when our hands are on the controls.
          </p>
        </div>

