      <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════
           PART 7: THE AI BEHIND THE GLASS
           ════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <section class="hiw__section" id="ai">
        <span class="hiw__part-label">Part 7</span>
        <h2>The AI Behind the Glass <a href="#ai" class="hiw__anchor"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path d="M10 13a5 5 0 0 0 7.54.54l3-3a5 5 0 0 0-7.07-7.07l-1.72 1.71"/><path d="M14 11a5 5 0 0 0-7.54-.54l-3 3a5 5 0 0 0 7.07 7.07l1.71-1.71"/></svg></a></h2>
        <div class="prose">
          <h3>Behind the Glass</h3>
          <p>
            In a traditional recording studio, the room is divided in two. The musician performs on one side of the glass. The engineer works the console on the other. They talk back and forth &mdash; "can I get more reverb in my headphones?" or "that last take felt rushed, let me try again" &mdash; and the session unfolds as a conversation between two people with different skills working toward the same goal. One makes the music. The other shapes the environment around it. Neither can do the other's job, and neither needs to.
          </p>
          <p>
            This studio works the same way, except the engineer is Claude, an AI assistant made by Anthropic. The dynamic is collaborative, not automated. Claude does not run a pre-programmed sequence of commands. It listens, responds, asks clarifying questions when something is ambiguous, and adapts to whatever the session needs in the moment. The musician drives the creative direction. Claude handles the technical execution. Between them, a session flows.
          </p>
          <h3>A Conversation, Not a Script</h3>
          <p>
            Claude connects to the Wing mixer through three tools: one that reads a parameter, one that changes a parameter, and one that dumps every setting on a channel at once. But the tools are not the interesting part. What matters is the conversation that wraps around them.
          </p>
          <p>
            The musician says "I'm not hearing the synth." Claude checks channel 11, finds it muted, unmutes it, and confirms. Simple. But the next request might be "set up for lead guitar" &mdash; which means activating an amp sim bus, setting the send level and mode, verifying the effect is loaded, and confirming the full signal path is live. The musician does not need to know any of those details. They just describe what they want, and Claude figures out the steps.
          </p>
          <p>
            Sometimes the conversation goes the other way. Claude notices something and speaks up. "Ch12 is at plus six with no EQ &mdash; that's hitting pretty hot. Want me to pull it back?" Or after making a routing change: "That stale send to Bus 12 was still active, I killed it." The relationship works both ways. The musician brings ears and taste. Claude brings precision and memory.
          </p>
          <h3>Troubleshooting Together</h3>
          <p>
            "The drums sound like shit" could mean anything. Too loud, too thin, too harsh, wrong routing. Claude investigates &mdash; dumps the drum channel, scans every parameter, and reports what it finds: fader at plus six dB, no EQ, a dynamics processor loaded but never enabled, a stale send leaking signal to an unused bus. The musician decides what to do about it. Claude executes the fix. This back-and-forth &mdash; diagnosis from the AI, judgment from the human &mdash; is how most problems get solved.
          </p>
          <p>
            Batch operations work the same way. "The mix sounds shrill on my phone" turns into a conversation about where to set the low-pass filter. Claude suggests 14 kHz as a starting point, applies it across all seven mix matrices, and the musician listens. "Still too bright." Claude pulls it down to 12 kHz. "That's better." The decision is human. The execution is instant.
          </p>
          <p>
            During one session, Claude discovered that the matrix EQ on the Wing uses numbered parameters instead of named ones &mdash; an undocumented quirk. It adapted on the fly, figured out the correct parameter indices by reading the raw data, applied the filters, and reported what it learned. That kind of improvisation in the face of unexpected hardware behavior is something a static script cannot do. It is also something a musician working alone would spend an hour troubleshooting in a manual.
          </p>
          <h3>Institutional Memory</h3>
          <p>
            At the start of every session, Claude reads two documents. The first is the studio configuration file &mdash; the complete map of every channel, bus, routing connection, and calibration value. Claude loads this so it knows that "the vocal" means channel 1 for the raw input and channel 17 for the processed return, or that Bus 5 is the electric guitar amp simulation. The second is the session lessons file &mdash; a running log updated after every session that catalogs every mistake and how it was fixed, every routing discovery, every quirk encountered.
          </p>
          <p>
            This means the studio has a memory that spans sessions. A mistake made on Tuesday &mdash; a muted channel that killed a recording path, a USB input mismatch that caused silence &mdash; becomes a lesson that prevents the same mistake on Thursday. The musician does not need to remember every technical detail from every session. Claude remembers for both of them.
          </p>
          <h3>Better Together</h3>
          <p>
            The point is not that Claude replaces the engineer. It is that the musician and the AI together can do what neither could do alone. The musician cannot memorize 400 parameters across 40 channels. Claude cannot hear that the guitar tone needs more bite. The musician cannot instantly apply filters to seven buses in parallel. Claude cannot feel that the chorus needs to hit harder. Each one fills in where the other falls short, and the session moves at the speed of the conversation rather than the speed of the interface.
          </p>
        </div>

