      <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════
           PART 8: THE DOCUMENTS
           ════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <section class="hiw__section" id="documents">
        <span class="hiw__part-label">Part 8</span>
        <h2>The Documents That Run the Studio <a href="#documents" class="hiw__anchor"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path d="M10 13a5 5 0 0 0 7.54.54l3-3a5 5 0 0 0-7.07-7.07l-1.72 1.71"/><path d="M14 11a5 5 0 0 0-7.54-.54l-3 3a5 5 0 0 0 7.07 7.07l1.71-1.71"/></svg></a></h2>
        <div class="prose">
          <h3>Why Documentation Matters</h3>
          <p>
            A studio is more than hardware and software. It is also knowledge &mdash; the accumulated understanding of how everything is connected, why certain decisions were made, what went wrong in the past, and how to avoid repeating those mistakes. In most studios, that knowledge lives in the engineer's head. When the engineer leaves, the knowledge goes with them, and the next person has to rediscover everything from scratch. We took a different approach: everything is written down.
          </p>
          <p>
            This is not bureaucracy. It is institutional memory &mdash; the kind that makes the studio smarter over time rather than dependent on any single person's recall. Four documents form the backbone of the system, and each one serves a distinct purpose.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="hiw__svg-wrap">
          <svg viewBox="0 0 700 260" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" role="img" aria-label="Four documents connected by reference lines">
            <!-- Document 1: studio.edn (top left) -->
