              <text x="0" y="52" text-anchor="middle" font-family="var(--body)" font-size="10" fill="var(--slate)">as they happen. Building</text>
              <text x="0" y="66" text-anchor="middle" font-family="var(--body)" font-size="10" fill="var(--slate)">the studio in public.</text>
            </g>

            <!-- Connection line: studio.edn -> session lessons -->
            <line x1="100" y1="110" x2="100" y2="160" stroke="var(--linen)" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="4,3"/>

            <!-- Connection line: session lessons -> blog -->
            <line x1="170" y1="200" x2="530" y2="200" stroke="var(--linen)" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="4,3"/>

            <!-- Connection line: OSC ref -> blog -->
            <line x1="600" y1="110" x2="600" y2="160" stroke="var(--linen)" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="4,3"/>

            <!-- Diagonal connections -->
            <line x1="170" y1="100" x2="530" y2="168" stroke="var(--linen)" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="4,3" opacity="0.5"/>
            <line x1="170" y1="168" x2="530" y2="100" stroke="var(--linen)" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="4,3" opacity="0.5"/>
          </svg>
        </div>

        <div class="prose">
          <h3>The Configuration File</h3>
          <p>
            The configuration file is the single source of truth. Written in EDN (a structured data format that both humans and machines can parse), it describes every channel in the mixer, every bus, every matrix output, every outboard connection, every patchbay point, every USB routing assignment, and every calibration value. When Claude needs to know which channel the vocal compressor return lives on, it reads this file. When a new piece of gear is added, this file gets updated. There is never a question about "how is this wired?" because the answer is always in the same place.
          </p>
          <h3>The Parameter Schema</h3>
          <p>
            The OSC reference is the mixer's complete command language, compressed into a format that Claude can load efficiently. OSC (Open Sound Control) is the protocol &mdash; a system of text commands that control the mixer remotely. Every fader, every mute button, every EQ parameter, every effect setting has an OSC address, and this reference catalogs all of them. It is the dictionary that allows Claude to translate "unmute channel 11" into the specific command the mixer understands.
          </p>
          <h3>The Lessons Log</h3>
          <p>
            The session lessons document is perhaps the most important of all. It is updated after every recording session with a brutally honest account of what went wrong and how it was fixed. A bus send that was leaking signal to the wrong output. A phantom power setting left on from a previous session that caused a massive noise floor. A USB routing assignment that conflicts with another channel. Every mistake is documented, every fix is recorded, and every session starts with Claude reading this file so it knows the full history of the studio's failures and solutions. The result is a system that genuinely learns: a mistake made in March is never repeated in April, because the lesson is written down and the AI reads it every time.
          </p>
          <h3>The Blog</h3>
          <p>
            The blog is the public-facing version of this philosophy. Real stories from real sessions, published as they happen. How we solved a routing problem. Why we moved tape saturation from the recording phase to the mixing phase. What it sounds like when you accidentally create a feedback loop through the USB bus. Building the studio in public means that anyone following along can learn from our process &mdash; and it holds us accountable to document everything clearly enough that an outsider could understand it.
          </p>
          <h3>A Studio That Learns</h3>
          <p>
            Together, these documents embody a belief that documentation is not overhead &mdash; it is infrastructure. The studio improves autonomously because everything is written down, every mistake teaches something, and the AI that runs the board starts each session with the complete accumulated knowledge of every session that came before it.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════
           CONCLUSION
           ════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <section class="hiw__section hiw__section--last" id="conclusion">
        <h2>The Whole Picture <a href="#conclusion" class="hiw__anchor"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path d="M10 13a5 5 0 0 0 7.54.54l3-3a5 5 0 0 0-7.07-7.07l-1.72 1.71"/><path d="M14 11a5 5 0 0 0-7.54-.54l-3 3a5 5 0 0 0 7.07 7.07l1.71-1.71"/></svg></a></h2>
        <div class="prose">
          <p>
            Here is the full journey in a single breath. You plug in your instrument. The patchbay, silently normalled, routes your signal through a Neve-style preamp that adds warmth and body, through a fast 1176-style compressor that catches the transients, through a slow compressor that smooths the overall dynamics, and through a de-esser that tames any harshness. The fully processed signal arrives at the mixer, which sends it to the recorder over USB while simultaneously routing it to your headphones with zero latency. You hear yourself sounding like a finished record while you perform. Logic captures the take. You record another layer on top, hearing the first take in your headphones alongside your live performance. Layer by layer, the song builds. When every part is down, the mixer adds effects &mdash; reverb, doubling, bass thickening, amp simulation &mdash; splits the audio into seven stems, and sends them to a physical mixing console. You ride the faders through the arrangement, performing the mix in real time, and the stereo result rolls onto a track. The best pass wins.
          </p>
          <p>
            The three promises are all delivered through this chain. Zero latency, because the monitoring path runs through hardware, not software, and the musician hears the processed sound in real time. Finished sound from the first take, because the outboard gear is calibrated and committed &mdash; what gets recorded is what gets released. And an AI running the board, because Claude reads the studio's complete configuration and session history at the start of every session, understands the mixer's full command language, and translates plain-language requests into precise technical operations without the musician ever touching the console.
          </p>
          <p>
            The philosophy behind all of it is simple: commit to the sound at the source, build the arrangement layer by layer, and perform the mix. Do not defer decisions to a future that never comes. Do not hide behind infinite undo. Trust the gear, trust the chain, and trust that a performance captured with intention and commitment has more life than one assembled from a hundred uncommitted options.
          </p>
          <p>
            And the studio gets smarter. Every session ends with lessons documented. Every mistake becomes a lesson that prevents the next mistake. The configuration file stays current. The blog tells the story. The AI reads it all and starts the next session knowing everything the studio has ever learned. It is a system designed not just to make records, but to improve at making records &mdash; autonomously, incrementally, session after session.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

    </article>
